{"title_page": "Sturgill Simpson", "text_new": "{{Short description|American country music singer-songwriter}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=June 2019}}\n{{Infobox musical artist\n| name = Sturgill Simpson\n| background = solo_singer\n| image = Sturgill Simpson photo 2016 (cropped).jpg\n| caption = Simpson in 2016\n| birth_name = John Sturgill Simpson<ref name=BMI-RepertoireProfile>{{cite web|url=http://repertoire.bmi.com/Catalog.aspx?detail=writerid&page=1&fromrow=1&torow=25&keyid=1583776&subid=0|title=Songwriter/Composer: Simpson, John Sturgill|work=[[Broadcast Music, Inc.|BMI]]}}</ref>\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1978|06|08}}\n| birth_place = [[Jackson, Kentucky|Jackson]], [[Kentucky]], U.S.\n| genre = {{flatlist|\n* [[Country music|Country]]<ref name=\"allmusic\"/>\n* [[outlaw country]]<ref name=\"allmusic\"/>\n* [[Americana (music)|Americana]]<ref name=\"allmusic\"/>\n* [[alternative country]]<ref name=\"allmusic\"/>\n}}\n| occupation = {{flatlist|\n* Singer-songwriter\n* actor\n}}\n| instrument = {{flatlist|\n* Vocals\n* guitar\n}}\n| years_active = 2004\u2013present\n| label = {{flatlist|\n* High Top Mountain\n* [[Atlantic Records|Atlantic]]\n* [[Elektra Records|Elektra]]\n}}\n| website = {{official URL}}\n}}\n'''John Sturgill Simpson''' (born June 8, 1978)<ref name=FamilySearch-KYBirthIndex-1978>{{cite web|title=John Sturgill Simpson - Kentucky, Vital Record Indexes|url=https://familysearch.org/ark:/61903/1:1:QKHX-K29M|website=[[FamilySearch]]}}</ref><ref name=FamilySearch-USPR-1998>{{cite web|title=J Sturgill Simpson, United States Public Records, 1970\u20132009|url=https://familysearch.org/pal:/MM9.1.1/QJ83-DWT2|website=[[FamilySearch]]}}</ref> is an American [[country music]] singer-songwriter and actor.<ref name=GQ-3CountryBadasses-2016>{{cite news|last1=Welch|first1=Will|title=Meet Three Country Badasses Who Are Shaking Up the Nashville Establishment|url=https://www.gq.com/story/meet-the-country-badasses-from-nashville|work=[[GQ]]|date=January 7, 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"the-hunt\">{{cite web|url=https://www.stereogum.com/2053096/sturgill-simpson-the-hunt-blumhouse-horror-movie/video/|title=See Hollywood\u2019s Hottest New Star Sturgill Simpson In The Trailer For Horror Movie The Hunt|last=Helman|first=Peter|date=July 30, 2019|work=Stereogum}}</ref> As of September 2019, he has released four albums as a solo artist. He released two albums independently, ''[[High Top Mountain]]'' in 2013<ref name=CountryWeekly-HightTop-2013>{{cite news|last1=Freeman|first1=Jon|url=http://www.countryweekly.com/music/edge-sturgill-simpson|title=On the Edge: Sturgill Simpson|work=[[Country Weekly]]|date=October 16, 2013}}</ref> and ''[[Metamodern Sounds in Country Music]]'' in 2014.<ref name=GQ-Warrior-2016>{{cite news|last1=Welch|first1=Will|title=The GQ&A: Sturgill Simpson, Country Music's Psychedelic Warrior-Philosopher|url=https://www.gq.com/story/sturgill-simpson-country-music-interview|work=[[GQ]]|date=January 7, 2016}}</ref> His second album was nominated for a [[Grammy Award for Best Americana Album]],<ref name=Grammy-NominationsList-2014>{{cite web|title=57th Grammy Awards: Final Nominations List|url=http://www.grammy.com/files/pages/57thpresslist12042014-with_aoy.pdf|website=[[Grammys]]|publisher=[[National Academy of Recording Arts & Sciences, Inc.]]|year=2014}}</ref> listed 18th on ''[[Rolling Stone]]''{{'}}s \"50 Best Albums of 2014,\"<ref name=RStone-50Best-2014>{{cite news|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/lists/50-best-albums-of-2014-20141201/sturgill-simpson-metamodern-sounds-in-country-music-20141201|title=50 Best Albums of 2014. 18: Sturgill Simpson, 'Metamodern Sounds in Country Music'|work=[[Rolling Stone]]|date=December 1, 2014}}</ref> and named among \"[[NPR]]'s 50 Favorite Albums of 2014.\"<ref name=NPR-50Best-2014>{{cite news|last1=Hilton|first1=Robin|url=https://www.npr.org/2014/12/08/368731400/npr-musics-50-favorite-albums-of-2014|title=NPR Music's 50 Favorite Albums Of 2014|publisher=[[NPR]]|date=December 8, 2014}}</ref> His third studio album, ''[[A Sailor's Guide to Earth]]'', was released on [[Atlantic Records]] and was Simpson's first major-label release,<ref name=Pitchfork-SailorsGuide-2016>{{cite news|url=http://pitchfork.com/news/63936-sturgill-simpson-announces-new-album-a-sailors-guide-to-earth-shares-brace-for-impact-live-a-little/|last1=Strauss|first1=Matthew|title=Sturgill Simpson Announces New Album A Sailor's Guide to Earth, Shares \"Brace for Impact (Live a Little)\"|work=[[Pitchfork Media]]|date=March 4, 2016}}</ref> later earning him [[Grammy Award for Best Country Album|Best Country Album]] at the [[59th Annual Grammy Awards|59th Grammy Awards]] while also being nominated for [[Grammy Award for Album of the Year|Album of the Year]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.latimes.com/entertainment/music/la-et-ms-grammys-2017-nominations-winners-list-20161205-story.html|title=Grammys 2017: Complete list of winners and nominees|work=[[Los Angeles Times]]|date=February 12, 2017}}</ref> Simpson's fourth album, ''[[Sound & Fury (Sturgill Simpson album)|Sound & Fury]]'', was released on September 27, 2019.\n\n==Early life==\nSimpson was born in [[Jackson, Kentucky|Jackson]], [[Breathitt County, Kentucky|Breathitt County]], [[Kentucky]],<ref name=\"allmusic\">{{cite web|url=http://www.allmusic.com/artist/sturgill-simpson-mn0003098721/biography|title=Sturgill Simpson {{!}} Biography & History {{!}} AllMusic|website=AllMusic|access-date=March 3, 2017}}</ref> the only child<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.vice.com/en_us/article/mb9jjq/the-final-interview-with-sturgill-simpson-according-to-sturgill-simpson|title=The Final Interview with Sturgill Simpson, According to Sturgill Simpson|first1=Jessica|last1=Lehrman|first2=Eric|last2=Sundermann|first3=Annalise|last3=Domenighini|date=November 30, 2017|accessdate=June 19, 2019}}</ref> of a secretary and a [[Kentucky State Police]] Trooper,  who formerly worked undercover in narcotics.<ref name=FamilySearch-USPR-1998 /><ref name=Fader-Freewheeling-2014>{{cite web|last1=Cooper|first1=Duncan|title=Another Country: A Freewheeling Hour with Sturgill Simpson|url=http://www.thefader.com/2014/07/15/another-country-interview-sturgill-simpson/|website=[[The Fader]]|date=July 15, 2014}}</ref> Due to his father's work, Simpson's family moved to [[Versailles, Kentucky|Versailles]], outside [[Lexington, Kentucky|Lexington]], where Simpson graduated from [[Woodford County High School (Kentucky)|Woodford County High School]].<ref name=Fader-Freewheeling-2014 /> Simpson's mother's family were coal miners.<ref name=NPR-WEdition-MakeArt-2014>{{cite web|last1=Martin|first1=Rachel|title='I Wanna Make Art': Sturgill Simpson's Twisting Path To Nashville|url=https://www.npr.org/2014/05/25/315292234/i-wanna-make-art-sturgill-simpsons-twisting-path-to-nashville|website=[[Weekend Edition]] Sunday|publisher=[[NPR]]|date=May 25, 2014}}</ref> Simpson is the first male on his mother's side of the family to not work in a strip mine or deep mine.<ref name=CharlieRose-SailorsGuide-2016>{{cite news|last1=Rose|first1=Charlie|title=Sturgill Simpson - Charlie Rose|url=https://charlierose.com/videos/29307|work=[[Charlie Rose (TV series)|Charlie Rose]]|date=October 13, 2016}}</ref>\n\nHe described his educational career by noting that he was \"not a great student\".<ref name = RS>{{cite web|last1=Ritz|first1=David|title=The Fighting Side of Sturgill Simpson|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/country/features/the-fighting-side-of-sturgill-simpson-w443513|work=[[Rolling Stone]]|accessdate=May 2, 2018|date=October 6, 2016}}</ref>  His parents divorced when he was in the seventh grade, and he sold drugs and experimented with [[LSD]] during high school.  He enlisted in the [[United States Navy]] his senior year of high school, and only \"barely graduated\".<ref name = RS/>\n\nAfter three years in the Navy, where he worked in the [[Combat Information Center]], Simpson spent time in Japan, then  lived in [[Everett, Washington|Everett]], [[Washington (state)|Washington]], and Seattle, where he waited tables at [[IHOP]], then moved back home to [[Lexington, Kentucky|Lexington]], [[Kentucky]].<ref name = RS/><ref name=Ky-LongRoad-2013>{{cite web|url=http://www.kentucky.com/2013/05/30/2658698/sturgill-simpson-took-a-long-road.html|title=Kentucky native Sturgill Simpson took long road, and railroad, to Nashville|last=Tunis|first=Walter|date=May 30, 2013|work=[[Lexington Herald-Leader]]}}</ref><ref name=Maron-WTFPodcast-2016>{{cite news|last1=Maron|first1=Marc|title=Episode 706 - Sturgill Simpson / John C. Reilly|url=http://www.wtfpod.com/podcast/episode-706-sturgill-simpson-john-c-reilly|work=[[WTF with Marc Maron|WTF with Marc Maron Podcast]]|date=May 12, 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\n===2004\u22122013: Early performances and recordings ===\nSimpson formed the Country/Rock band Sunday Valley in 2004, for which he played Guitar/Vocals,<ref name = RS/> which played at the Pickathon festival in [[Portland, Oregon]].<ref name=AllMusic-Bio>{{cite web|url=http://www.allmusic.com/artist/sturgill-simpson-mn0003098721/biography|title=Sturgill Simpson: Biography|last=Erlewine|first=Stephen Thomas|website=[[AllMusic]]}}</ref>\n\nSimpson took a break from music, focusing on building a career at a [[Salt Lake City]] railroad freight-shipping yard for [[Union Pacific Railroad]], which he eventually ended up managing. He credits his wife and friends with supporting what he characterized as a hobbyist focus on songwriting and playing to convincing him to actually focus on getting serious and trying to make music for a living.<ref name=CharlieRose-SailorsGuide-2016 /> After playing local open mics and gigs, Simpson returned to Sunday Valley. The band toured and made an album. He and his wife moved to [[Nashville]] when the group disbanded in 2012.<ref name=WSJ-CountryMeta-2014>{{cite news|last1=Dougherty|first1=Steve|title=Sturgill Simpson Sings Country Metaphysics|url=https://online.wsj.com/news/articles/SB10001424052702304101504579543640189785928|work=[[The Wall Street Journal]]|date=May 6, 2014}}</ref>\n\nAfter going solo, Simpson released his debut album ''[[High Top Mountain]]'' in 2013, which he self-funded, self-released, and had cut in Nashville <ref name=AllMusic-Bio/><ref>{{cite journal|last1=Hughes|first1=Rob|title=Sturgill Simpson|journal=Uncut|date=March 2014|issue=202|page=83}}</ref><ref name=Fader-GenF-2014>{{cite web|last1=Cooper|first1=Duncan|title=GEN F: Sturgill Simpson, the Cosmic Cowboy of the Digital Age Read|url=http://www.thefader.com/2014/05/12/gen-f-sturgill-simpson-interview/|website=[[The Fader]]|date=May 12, 2014}}</ref> before signing to British independent label [[Loose Music|Loose]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://loosemusic.com/sturgillsimpson/new-loose-signing-sturgill-simpson|title=Loose {{!}}   New Loose Signing: Sturgill Simpson!|website=loosemusic.com}}</ref> who released the album in Europe in 2014.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://loosemusic.com/sturgillsimpson/sturgill-simpsons-high-top-mountain-out-today|title=Loose {{!}}   Sturgill Simpson's High Top Mountain, out today!|website=loosemusic.com}}</ref> The album was produced by [[Dave Cobb]]. Among the session musicians were [[Hargus \"Pig\" Robbins]] on piano and [[Robby Turner]], a former guitarist for [[Waylon Jennings]], on [[steel guitar]].<ref name=\"Ky-LongRoad-2013\"/> The record is named after a cemetery near Jackson where many of Simpson's family members are buried.<ref name=AmSongwriter-ManHour-2013>{{cite web|last1=Inman|first1=Davis|title=Sturgill Simpson: Man Of The Hour|url=http://www.americansongwriter.com/2013/04/sturgill-simpson-man-of-the-hour/|website=[[American Songwriter]]|date=April 26, 2013}}</ref> [[Stephen Thomas Erlewine]] of [[AllMusic]] rated ''High Top Mountain'' 3 and half stars out of 5, comparing its sound favorably to Waylon Jennings.<ref name=AllMusic-HighTop_2013>{{cite web|url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/high-top-mountain-mw0002529932|title=''High Top Mountain''|last=Erlewine|first=Stephen Thomas|website=[[AllMusic]]}}</ref> The album's style has also been compared to [[Merle Haggard]]'s.<ref name=Fader-GenF-2014/> Erik Ernst of the ''[[Milwaukee Journal-Sentinel]]'' also compared it to Jennings, saying that it had \"rich vintage sounds, heartbreaking ballads, and juke-joint ramblers\".<ref name=MilwaukeeJournalSent-Review-2013>{{cite web|url=http://www.jsonline.com/entertainment/musicandnightlife/cd-reviews-jason-isbell-alison-moyet-walter-trout-sturgill-simpson-b9927487z1-211021241.html|title=CD reviews: Jason Isbell, Alison Moyet, Walter Trout, Sturgill Simpson|date=June 11, 2013|work=[[Milwaukee Journal-Sentinel]]|last=Ernst|first=Erik}}</ref>\n\n=== 2014\u20132016: ''Metamodern Sounds in Country Music'' ===\n[[File:SturgillSimpson.jpg|thumb|Simpson in 2013]]\nIn 2014, Simpson released his second album produced by Dave Cobb, ''[[Metamodern Sounds in Country Music]]'' to positive reviews.<ref name=Pitchfork-MetaReview-2014>{{cite web|last1=Deusner|first1=Stephen M.|title=Sturgill Simpson, Metamodern Sounds in Country Music|url=http://pitchfork.com/reviews/albums/19386-sturgill-simpson-metamodern-sounds-in-country-music/|website=[[Pitchfork Media]]|date=May 16, 2014}}</ref><ref name=NYTimes-CountryLament-2014>{{cite news|last1=Caramanica|first1=Jon|title=A Country Lament Sinks Into Despair: Sturgill Simpson's 'Metamodern Sounds in Country Music'|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2014/05/15/arts/music/sturgill-simpsons-metamodern-sounds-in-country-music.html|work=[[The New York Times]]|date=May 14, 2014}}</ref><ref name=Esquire-BestDarkestWeirdest-2014>{{cite web|last1=Keohane|first1=Joe|title=The Best, Darkest, Weirdest Country Record of the Year|url=http://www.esquire.com/blogs/culture/sturgill-simpson-life-of-sin|website=[[Esquire (magazine)|Esquire]]|date=May 1, 2014}}</ref><ref name=Billboard-Shuns-2014>{{cite news|last1=Dauphin|first1=Chuck|title=Sturgill Simpson Shuns 'Tailgating and Spring Breaks' on New Album|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/the-615/6091967/sturgill-simpson-shuns-tailgating-and-spring-breaks-on-new-album|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|date=May 16, 2014}}</ref> The album's lead single is \"Living the Dream\".<ref name=Paste-Dream-2014>{{cite web|url=http://www.pastemagazine.com/blogs/av/2014/02/song-premiere-sturgill-simpson---living-the-dream.html|title=Song Premiere: Sturgill Simpson \u2013 \"Living The Dream\"|last=Rowland|first=Sarah|date=February 20, 2014|work=[[Paste Magazine]]}}</ref> The record is described as a \"deep and unconventional relationship between traditionalism and new ways of thinking,\" and deviates from Simpson's more traditional hard country debut.<ref name=NPR-GodsDrugsLizardAliens-2014>{{cite web|last1=Powers|first1=Ann|title=God, Drugs And Lizard Aliens: Yep, It's Country Music|url=https://www.npr.org/blogs/therecord/2014/04/17/304075384/god-drugs-and-lizard-aliens-yep-its-country-music|publisher=[[NPR]]|date=April 17, 2014}}</ref> Simpson said that \"recording and mixing was done in five and a half days for about $4,000. I was pretty proud about that.\"<ref name=AmSongwriter-MysticQ&A-2014>{{cite web|last1=Trageser|first1=Stephen|title=Mystic Mind: A Q&A with Sturgill Simpson|url=http://www.americansongwriter.com/2014/07/mystic-mind-qa-sturgill-simpson/|website=[[American Songwriter]]|date=July 23, 2014}}</ref> The album made two separate \"Top Albums of 2014\" lists in ''[[The New York Times]]'' (ranking 4th<ref name=NYTimes-Top10-2014>{{cite news|last=Caramanica|first=Jon|title=Jon Caramanica's Top 10 Albums of 2014|work=[[The New York Times]]|date=December 11, 2014|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2014/12/14/arts/music/jon-caramanica-looks-at-the-albums-of-2014.htm}}</ref> and 8th<ref name=NYTimes-ChinenTop-2014>{{cite news|last1=Chinen|first1=Nate|title=Nate Chinen's Top Albums of 2014, With Beyonc\u00e9, Fred Hersch Trio and More|work=[[The New York Times]]|date=December 11, 2014|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2014/12/14/arts/music/authoritative-albums-from-beyonc-fred-hersch-trio-and-more.html}}</ref>) and was also called the best album of the year by ''[[American Songwriter]]''.<ref name=\"ASBest2014\">{{cite news|title=American Songwriter's Top 50 Albums of 2014: Presented by D'Addario|work=[[American Songwriter]]|date=November 24, 2014|url=http://americansongwriter.com/2014/11/american-songwriters-top-50-albums-2014/5/}}</ref>\n\nSimpson made his US network television debut on July 14, 2014, on the ''[[Late Show with David Letterman]]'', playing \"Life of Sin\".<ref name=RStone-Letterman-2014>{{cite web|last1=Hudak|first1=Joseph|title=Sturgill Simpson Makes 'Letterman' Debut: Kentucky singer-songwriter wows Dave with \"Life of Sin\"|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/videos/sturgill-simpson-makes-letterman-debut-20140715|website=[[Rolling Stone (magazine)|Rolling Stone]]|date=July 15, 2014}}</ref> That year, he would go on to play \"Living the Dream\" on a September episode of ''[[Conan (talk show)|Conan]]'',<ref name=RollingStone-Conan-LivingDream-2014>{{cite news|title=Watch Sturgill Simpson Live the 'Dream' With Conan O'Brien|work=[[Rolling Stone]]|date=September 11, 2014|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/videos/sturgill-simpson-living-the-dream-conan-video-20140911}}</ref> \"[[Turtles All the Way Down (song)|Turtles All the Way Down]]\" on an October episode of ''[[The Tonight Show Starring Jimmy Fallon]]'',<ref name=RollingStone-Fallon-Turtles-2014>{{cite news|last1=Hudak|first1=Joseph|title=Sturgill Simpson Explores Space and Time with 'Turtles' Performance on 'Fallon'|work=[[Rolling Stone]]|date=October 29, 2014|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/videos/sturgill-simpson-performs-turtles-tonight-show-fallon-20141029}}</ref> and \"[[The Promise (When in Rome song)|The Promise]]\" on a December episode of ''[[Late Night with Seth Meyers]]''.<ref name=\"RSMeyers\">{{cite news|last=Moss|first=Marissa R.|title=Watch Sturgill Simpson Perform a Lost Eighties Hit on 'Seth Meyers'|work=[[Rolling Stone]]|date=December 11, 2014|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/videos/watch-sturgill-simpson-perform-a-lost-eighties-hit-on-seth-meyers-20141211}}</ref> In 2015, he returned to ''The Late Show'' and ''Conan'' playing \"Long White Line\" in February and \"Just Let Go\" in April (respectively).<ref name=\"RSLetterman\">{{cite news|last=Moss|first=Marissa R.|title=Watch Sturgill Simpson Reincarnate 'Long White Line' on 'Letterman'|work=[[Rolling Stone]]|date=February 13, 2015|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/videos/watch-sturgill-simpson-reincarnate-long-white-line-on-letterman-20150213}}</ref><ref name=RollingStone-Conan-JustLetGo-2015>{{cite news|title=Watch Sturgill Simpson 'Just Let Go' With Super-Sized Band on 'Conan'|work=[[Rolling Stone]]|date=April 15, 2015|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/videos/watch-sturgill-simpson-just-let-go-with-super-sized-band-on-conan-20150415}}</ref> He has also played the [[Grand Ole Opry]]<ref name=NPR-WEdition-MakeArt-2014 /> and at [[Austin City Limits]]. He has opened for artists like [[Dwight Yoakam]], [[Willie Nelson]],<ref name=ACL-WillieNelson-2014>{{cite web|title=Willie Nelson 2014 - 12/30|url=http://acl-live.com/calendar/willie-nelson-2014-12-30|website=[[Austin City Limits]] Live}}</ref> Merle Haggard,<ref name=\"Boot\">{{cite news|last=Vinson|first=Christina|title=Merle Haggard Praises Sturgill Simpson, Calls Modern Country Music 'Crap'|work=The Boot|date=September 4, 2015|url=http://theboot.com/merle-haggard-sturgill-simpson-modern-country-music-crap/}}</ref> and the [[Zac Brown Band]].<ref name=SavingCountry-WhereGo-2014>{{cite web|last1=Trigger|title=Where Does Sturgill Simpson Go From Here?|url=http://www.savingcountrymusic.com/where-does-sturgill-simpson-go-from-here|website=Saving Country Music|date=May 16, 2014}}</ref>\n\nHis cover of \"The Promise\" by 1980s band [[When in Rome (band)|When In Rome]] was featured in the Season 2 Episode 9 of the HBO series ''[[The Leftovers (TV series)|The Leftovers]]'' in November 2015.<ref name=SavingCountry-Leftovers-2015>{{cite news|title=Sturgill Simpson Featured on HBO's \"The Leftovers\"|work=Saving Country Music|date=November 30, 2015|url=http://www.savingcountrymusic.com/sturgill-simpson-featured-on-hbos-the-leftovers/}}</ref> The first track from this album, \"Turtles All The Way Down,\" was featured in the soundtrack for Season 1 Episode 5 of HBO's series ''[[Watchmen (TV series)|Watchmen]]'' in November 2019.<ref name=Watchmen-Soundtrack>https://www.tunefind.com/show/watchmen/season-1/93019</ref> Simpson also wrote and performed the theme song to the [[Martin Scorsese]]/[[Mick Jagger]]-produced TV show, ''[[Vinyl (TV series)|Vinyl]].'' The song is called \"Sugar Daddy.\"<ref name=DallasObserver-SugarDaddy-2016>{{cite news|last1=McCarthy|first1=Amy|title=Sturgill Simpson Hasn't Betrayed Country Music Because He Never Was A Country Artist|url=http://www.dallasobserver.com/music/sturgill-simpson-hasnt-betrayed-country-music-because-he-never-was-a-country-artist-8105852|work=[[Dallas Observer]]|date=March 9, 2016}}</ref> As of July 2015, Simpson's songs are represented by [[Downtown Music Publishing]]\u2014an agreement that followed his record deal with [[Atlantic Records]].<ref name=Boot-DowntonMusic-2015>{{cite news|last=Allers|first=Hannahlee|title=Sturgill Simpson Signs With Downtown Music Publishing|work=The Boot|date=July 6, 2015|url=http://theboot.com/sturgill-simpson-downtown-music-publishing/}}</ref>\n\n=== 2016\u20132017: ''A Sailor's Guide to Earth''===\nIn March 2016, Simpson released the first track from his third album, ''[[A Sailor's Guide To Earth]]'', a song called \"Brace For Impact (Live A Little).\"<ref name=RStone-NirvanaNewRecord-2016>{{cite news|last1=Hudak|first1=Joseph|title=Sturgill Simpson on Staying Country, Covering Nirvana on New Album|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/sturgill-simpson-on-staying-country-covering-nirvana-on-new-album-20160321|work=[[Rolling Stone (magazine)|Rolling Stone]]|date=March 21, 2016}}</ref> The record is a commemoration of the birth of Simpson's son, and features work by [[Sharon Jones & The Dap-Kings|The Dap-Kings]] from [[Brooklyn]]'s [[Daptone Records]],<ref name=NPR-BraceImpactLiveLittle-2016>{{cite news|last1=Boilen|first1=Bob|title=Hear Thrilling New Music From Sturgill Simpson|url=https://www.npr.org/sections/allsongs/2016/03/04/469088013/hear-thrilling-new-music-from-sturgill-simpson|work=[[NPR]] All Songs Considered|date=March 4, 2016}}</ref> as well as a cover of [[Nirvana (band)|Nirvana's]], \"[[In Bloom]].\" Simpson self-produced the record \u2013 [[Dave Cobb]], who produced his prior records, did not work on this record, marking a departure from prior efforts.<ref name=DallasObserver-SugarDaddy-2016 /> Simpson also created the record with a focus on sequencing, and recorded tracks live.<ref name=RStone-NirvanaNewRecord-2016 /> The record marks his major label debut.<ref name=Maron-WTFPodcast-2016 /> It was nominated for [[Grammy Award for Album of the Year|Album of the Year]] and won [[Grammy Award for Best Country Album|Best Country Album]] at the [[59th Annual Grammy Awards|59th Grammy Awards]].<ref name=Grammy-Noms-2016>{{cite web|url=http://www.grammy.com/nominees|title=59th Annual GRAMMY Awards Nominees and Winners|work=The Grammys|date=December 6, 2016}}</ref> In January 2017, Simpson appeared on the [[Felicity Jones]]-hosted episode of ''[[Saturday Night Live]]'', playing \"Keep It Between the Lines\" and \"Call to Arms.\"<ref name=SNL-KeepItBetweenTheLines-2017>{{cite news|title=Watch Sturgill Simpson: Keep It Between the Lines from Saturday Night Live|url=http://www.nbc.com/saturday-night-live/video/sturgill-simpson-keep-it-between-the-lines/3454415?snl=1|work=[[Saturday Night Live]]|date=January 15, 2017}}</ref><ref name=SNL-CallToArms-2017>{{cite news|title=Watch Sturgill Simpson: Call To Arms from Saturday Night Live|url=http://www.nbc.com/saturday-night-live/video/sturgill-simpson-call-to-arms/3454433?snl=1|work=[[Saturday Night Live]]|date=January 15, 2017}}</ref>\n\nSimpson had planned to take a break from touring for the entirety of 2017 to focus on his family, but reconsidered after his Grammy nominations.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.savingcountrymusic.com/sturgill-simpson-announces-2017-tour-dates/|title=Sturgill Simpson Announces 2017 Tour Dates|work=Saving Country Music|date=February 9, 2017|accessdate=January 15, 2018}}</ref> He began touring again in May 2017 by playing a show at the Wharf Amphitheater in [[Orange Beach, Alabama]], with [[Margo Price]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://alwharf.com/calendar/C25995805D~Sturgill+Simpson+in+Concert.htm|title=Sturgill Simpson in Concert 5.06.17|publisher=The Wharf at Orange Beach|accessdate=January 15, 2018}}</ref> Simpson also performed as the opening act for three shows during the [[Guns N' Roses]] \"Not in this Lifetime\" tour in the summer of 2017.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://theboot.com/sturgill-simpson-guns-n-roses-2017-concerts/|title=Sturgill Simpson Joining Guns N' Roses for Three Summertime Shows|last=Stecker|first=Liv|work=[[Townsquare Media#Web publications and services|The Boot]]|date=May 25, 2017|accessdate=January 15, 2018}}</ref> Simpson helped produce fellow Kentucky singer/songwriter [[Tyler Childers]]' 2017 album ''Purgatory'' after being introduced to Childers by drummer Miles Miller.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/country/news/hear-sturgill-simpson-protege-tyler-childers-new-song-w489192|title=Hear Sturgill Simpson Protege Tyler Childers' New 'Whitehouse Road'|last=Moss|first=Marissa R.|work=[[Rolling Stone (magazine)|Rolling Stone]]|date=June 22, 2017|accessdate=January 15, 2018}}</ref>\n\n===2018\u2013present: ''Sound & Fury''===\nIn a March 5, 2018, interview on ''[[The Joe Rogan Experience]]'' podcast, Simpson revealed that he was working on his fourth studio album, and hinted that it would be a [[double album]], though this was ultimately not the case.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=R0IqNaE513w|title=Joe Rogan Experience #1087 - Sturgill Simpson|last=PowerfulJRE|date=March 5, 2018|accessdate=June 19, 2019|via=YouTube}}</ref> The title of the album, ''[[Sound & Fury (Sturgill Simpson album)|Sound & Fury]]'', was announced on July 21, 2019, at the [[San Diego Comic-Con]], with Simpson describing it as a \"sleazy, steamy rock'n'roll record\". A companion [[anime]] film bearing the same name was also released on [[Netflix]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-country/sturgill-simpson-new-album-anime-film-sound-and-fury-netflix-861660/|title=Sturgill Simpson Announces New Album, Anime Film 'Sound & Fury'|last=Kreps|first=Daniel|date=July 21, 2019|work=Rolling Stone}}</ref> The album was officially put up for pre-order on August 20, 2019, with the track \"Sing Along\" being released the same day. It was released on September 27, 2019, to positive reviews.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.metacritic.com/music/sound-fury/sturgill-simpson|title=Sound & Fury by Sturgill Simpson Reviews|website=[[Metacritic]]|accessdate=October 9, 2019}}</ref> The album broke with Simpson's established country style, featuring a fuzzy [[hard rock]] sound influenced by psychedelia and funk music.\n\nSimpson was originally going to perform at the [[Woodstock 50]] music festival in August 2019, before the festival's cancellation.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://consequenceofsound.net/2019/03/woodstock-50-lineup-leak/|title=Woodstock 2019: The Killers, Chance the Rapper, Imagine Dragons to headline 50th anniversary festival|date=March 5, 2019|accessdate=June 19, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cnn.com/2019/07/31/entertainment/woodstock-50-canceled/index.html|title=Woodstock 50 festival canceled|last=Gonzalez|first=Sandra|date=August 1, 2019|work=[[CNN]]}}</ref>\n\n==Band members==\n===Current members===\n* Chuck Bartels<ref name=GearPage-Bartels-2016>{{cite news|title=Who is Sturgill Simpson's new Bass Player|url=http://www.thegearpage.net/board/index.php?threads/who-is-sturgill-simpsons-new-bass-player.1696404/|website=theGearPage.net}}</ref> \u2013 bass guitar (2015\u2013present)\n* Bobby Emmett \u2013 keyboards (2012\u20132013, 2015\u2013present)\n* Miles Miller \u2013 drums, percussion, backing vocals (2012\u2013present)\n\n===Past members===\n* Kevin Black \u2013 bass guitar (2011\u20132015)\n* Laur Joamets \u2013 electric guitar (2013\u20132017)\n* Adam Davis \u2013 electric guitar (2012\u20132013)\n\n==Musical style==\n[[File:Sturgillguitar.jpg|thumb|Simpson with an acoustic guitar, pictured here in 2013]]\nSimpson is often compared to [[Waylon Jennings]]<ref name=Paste-MetaReview-2014>{{cite web|last1=Lore|first1=Mark|title=Sturgill Simpson: Metamodern Sounds In Country Music Review|url=http://www.pastemagazine.com/articles/2014/05/sturgill-simpson-metamodern-sounds-in-country-musi.html|website=[[Paste (magazine)|Paste]]|date=May 21, 2014}}</ref> and the [[outlaw country]] genre of country music.<ref name=Grantland-NewAgeOutlaw-2014>{{cite web|last1=Hyden|first1=Steven|title=The New-Age Outlaw Country of Lydia Loveless and Sturgill Simpson|url=http://grantland.com/hollywood-prospectus/the-new-age-outlaw-country-of-lydia-loveless-and-sturgill-simpson/|website=[[Grantland]]|date=April 30, 2014}}</ref> [[Shooter Jennings]] says, \"Sturgill isn't imitating at all, and he sounds like my favorite era of my dad, the Seventies, when he would sing quieter and more conversational. That's what struck me about Sturgill from Day One. And still does.\"<ref name=RStone-CountryMessiah-2014>{{cite web|last1=Hudak|first1=Joseph|title=Is Sturgill Simpson Country Music's Savior? Not If He Can Help It|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/is-sturgill-simpson-country-musics-savior-not-if-he-can-help-it-20140603|website=[[Rolling Stone (magazine)|Rolling Stone]]|date=June 3, 2014}}</ref> Simpson himself counts [[Merle Haggard]], [[Willie Nelson]], [[Keith Whitley]], and [[Marty Robbins]] as much bigger influences on his sound than Waylon Jennings.<ref name=\"RSInterview\">{{cite news|last=Leahey|first=Andrew|title=5 Things We Learned From Sturgill Simpson's Interview With Foos Guitarist|work=[[Rolling Stone]]|date=July 31, 2015|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/5-things-we-learned-from-sturgill-simpsons-interview-with-foos-guitarist-20150731}}</ref> Simpson has also stated he tries to base his career around that of [[Dwight Yoakam]]. Indeed, [[Country Music Television]] noted that Simpson had \"a voice that recalls Merle Haggard [and] guitar licks that bring [[Buck Owens]] to mind.\"<ref name=CMT-Metamodern-2014>{{cite news|last=Deusner|first=Stephen M.|title=Sturgill Simpson Puts a Metamodern Spin on Country Music|publisher=[[Country Music Television]]|date=May 16, 2014|url=http://www.cmtedge.com/2014/05/16/sturgill-simpson-puts-a-metamodern-spin-on-country-music/}}</ref> His overall sound was described by [[Indiewire]] as \"a mesmerizing and sometimes bewildering mix of traditional country sounds, contemporary philosophy, and psychedelic recording-studio wizardry.\"<ref name=Indiewire-Interview-2014>{{cite news|last=Abramson|first=Seth|title=Metamericana: Outlaw Country Goes Psychedelic: An Interview with Sturgill Simpson on His Music Videos|work=[[Indiewire]]|date=August 14, 2014|url=http://blogs.indiewire.com/pressplay/outlaw-country-goes-psychedelic-an-interview-with-sturgill-simpson-on-his-music-videos-20140814}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nSimpson is married and in 2018 he revealed he and his family reside in the Smoky Mountain area.<ref name=Fader-Freewheeling-2014 /> He has three sons.<ref name=WSJ-CountryMeta-2014 /><ref name=CountryStandardTime-Metamodern-2014>{{cite web|last1=Barker|first1=Brian|title=Simpson Gets Metamodern|url=http://www.countrystandardtime.com/d/article.asp?xid=1163|website=[[Country Standard Time]]|date=July 2014}}</ref> Simpson is a [[Kentucky Colonel]], having been honoured at the [[Kentucky State Capitol]] on March 20, 2018. Rep. [[James Kay (Kentucky politician)|James Kay]] described Simpson as \"independent\" and \"very proud to be from our great Commonwealth,\" calling ''Metamodern Sounds in Country Music'' \"one of the best albums of all time ... pure Kentucky and ... pure Sturgill Simpson.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://theboot.com/sturgill-simpson-kentucky-colonel/|title=Sturgill Simpson Honored By Kentucky Lawmakers, Is Now a Kentucky Colonel|last=Stefano|first=Angela|website=The Boot|date=March 21, 2018|accessdate=June 13, 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn April 11, 2020, Simpson tested positive for [[COVID-19]] after exhibiting symptoms for over a month and then cried about it on twitter like a little baby.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Hughes |first1=Hilary |title=Sturgill Simpson Confirms COVID-19 Diagnosis Following Frustrating Attempts to Get Tested |url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/9356569/sturgill-simpson-covid-19-positive |website=Billboard}}</ref>\n\n==Discography==\n===Albums===\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|-\n! rowspan=\"2\" style=\"width:20em;\"| Title\n! rowspan=\"2\" style=\"width:22em;\"| Album details\n! colspan=\"6\"| Peak chart positions\n! rowspan=\"2\" style=\"width:12em;\"| Sales\n|- style=\"font-size:smaller;\"\n! style=\"width:45px;\"| [[Billboard 200|US]]<br /><ref name=Billboard-200>{{cite web|url={{BillboardURLbyName|artist=Sturgill Simpson|chart=Billboard 200}}|title=Sturgill Simpson & Song Chart History \u2013 Billboard 200|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]}}</ref>\n! style=\"width:45px;\"| [[Top Country Albums|US<br>Country]]<br /><ref name=Billboard-Country>{{cite web|url={{BillboardURLbyName|artist=sturgill simpson|chart=Country Albums}}|title=Sturgill Simpson Chart History \u2013 Country Albums|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]}}</ref>\n! style=\"width:45px;\"| [[Top Rock Albums|US<br>Rock]]<br /><ref name=Billboard-Rock>{{cite web|url={{BillboardURLbyName|artist=sturgill simpson|chart=Rock Albums}}|title=Sturgill Simpson Chart History \u2013 Rock Albums|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]}}</ref>\n! style=\"width:45px;\"| [[Canadian Albums Chart|CAN]]<br /><ref name=Billboard-Canadian>{{cite web|url={{BillboardURLbyName|artist=Sturgill Simpson|chart=Canadian Albums}}|title=Sturgill Simpson Chart History \u2013 Canadian Albums|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]}}</ref>\n! style=\"width:45px;\"| [[VG-lista|NOR]]<br /><ref name=NorwegianCharts-Discog>{{cite web|url=http://norwegiancharts.com/showinterpret.asp?interpret=Sturgill+Simpson|title=Discography Sturgill Simpson|website=NorwegianCharts.com}}</ref>\n! style=\"width:45px;\"| [[UK Albums Chart|UK]]<br /><ref name=OfficialCharts-Albums>{{cite web|url=http://www.officialcharts.com/artist/31721/sturgill-simpson/|title=Sturgill Simpson|publisher=[[Official Charts Company]]|format=select \"Albums\" tab}}</ref>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| ''[[High Top Mountain]]''\n| \n* Release date: June 11, 2013\n* Labels: High Top Mountain, [[Loose Music|Loose]]\n* Formats: [[Compact disc|CD]], LP, digital\n| \u2014\n| 31\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n|\n*US: 105,600<ref name=\"roughstock jan2017\">{{cite news |url=http://roughstock.com/news/2017/01/41331-top-10-country-albums-chart-january-23-2016 |title=Top 10 Country Albums Chart: January 23, 2017 |first= Matt|last= Bjorke |date= January 22, 2017 |work=Roughstock }}</ref>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| ''[[Metamodern Sounds in Country Music]]''\n| \n* Release date: May 13, 2014\n* Labels: High Top Mountain, Loose\n* Formats: CD, LP, digital\n| 59\n| 8\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n|\n*US: 228,600<ref name=\"roughstock jan2017\"/>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| ''[[A Sailor's Guide to Earth]]''\n| \n* Release date: April 15, 2016\n* Label: [[Atlantic Records|Atlantic]]\n* Formats: CD, LP, digital\n| 3\n| 1\n| 1\n| 31\n| 34\n| 43 \n|\n*US: 217,900<ref>{{cite news |url=http://roughstock.com/news/2017/10/42358-top-10-country-albums-sales-chart-october-9-2017 |title=Top 10 Country Albums Sales Chart: October 9, 2017|first= Matt |last= Bjorke |date= October 10, 2017 |work=Roughstock }}</ref>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| ''[[Sound & Fury (Sturgill Simpson album)|Sound & Fury]]''\n| \n* Released: September 27, 2019<ref>{{cite web|url=https://pitchfork.com/news/sturgill-simpson-details-new-album-shares-new-song-sing-along-listen/|title=Sturgill Simpson Details New Album, Shares New Song \"Sing Along\": Listen|website=[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]]|last=Bloom|first=Madison|date=August 20, 2019|accessdate=August 20, 2019}}</ref>\n* Label: [[Elektra Records|Elektra]]\n* Formats: CD, LP, digital\n| 12\n| 3\n| 3\n| 55\n| \u2014\n| 79\n|\n*US: 72,900<ref>{{cite web |url=http://roughstock.com/news/2020/03/44165-top-10-country-albums-pure-sales-chart-march-9-2020|title=Top 10 Country Albums Pure Sales Chart: March 9, 2020 |work=RoughStock|first=Matt |last=Bjorke |date= March 10, 2020 |accessdate=March 22, 2020 }}</ref>\n|-\n| colspan=\"10\" style=\"font-size:8pt\"| \"\u2014\" denotes releases that did not chart\n|}\n\n===Singles===\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|-\n! rowspan=\"2\"| Year\n! rowspan=\"2\" style=\"width:20em;\"| Song\n! colspan=\"3\"| Peak chart positions\n! rowspan=\"2\"| Album\n|- style=\"font-size:smaller;\"\n! style=\"width:45px;\"| [[Adult Alternative Songs|US<br>AAA]]<br /><ref name=Billboard-AdultAlternative>{{cite web | title = Billboard: Adult Alternative Songs| url = https://www.billboard.com/music/sturgill-simpson/chart-history/triple-a|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]}}</ref>\n! style=\"width:45px;\"| [[Hot Country Songs|US Country]]<br /><ref name=Billboard-CountrySongs>{{cite web|url={{BillboardURLbyName|artist=Sturgill Simpson|chart=Country Songs}}|title=Sturgill Simpson & Song Chart History \u2013 Country Songs|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]}}</ref>\n! style=\"width:45px;\"| [[Rock Songs|US<br